node.undefined8:
Vitamin D3

Code: D3

What is Vitamin D3

 

Vitamin D is a fat-soluble vitamin which is produced endogenously in the body when suns ultraviolet rays hit the skin. 

It is also known as Sunshine Vitamin Or Cholecalciferol . It is hardly present in any food but is readily available as a supplement.

It us used for treating diseases like Osteoporosis or for improvement for overall health.

The problem with Vitamin D whether it is obtained from sunlight or in food or as a supplement is that this Vit D is biologically inert and has to undergo two chemical changes in the body (hydroxylations) for activation.
 

Calcidiol & Calcitrol

The first chemical reaction occurs in the liver and converts vitamin D to 25-hydroxyvitamin D [25(OH)D], also known as calcidiol.

The second occurs primarily in the kidney and forms the physiologically active 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D [1,25(OH)2D], also known as calcitriol 25-hydroxy vitamin D blood test is the best indicator of Vitamin D status in the body.

25(OH)D has a half life of 2-3 week . On the contrary the bioactive hormone is 1,25(OH)2D acting both at the receptor level and by non-genomic mechanisms; its half life is 4-15 hours

It is metabolized through the liver with a half life of around 4 hours. One important fact to remember is that initial damage to the liver will not reflect in changes in the liver function test so this drug level is the best way to monitor toxicity. For half-life determination , take 2 specimens 4 hours apart and not the time of each draw. Half life can then be calculated accordingly. First specimen has to be drawn no sooner than 2 hours after ingestion of paracetamol.

node.name: ACID FAST STAIN
node.undefined6: acid fast stain, acid fast bacilli stain, AFBMS,ACID FAST STAIN
node.undefined8: Acid fast staining is a standard staining technique for demonstration of acid fast bacilli i.e. Mycobacterium tuberculosis (TB BACILLI) and other atypical Mycobacteria. Ziel-Neelsen Technique and its different modifications are used as acid fast staining technique. The acid fast staining reaction of Mycobacteria, along with their characteristic size and shape, is a valuable aid in the early detection of infection and monitoring of therapy for Mycobacterial diseases. Pus, tissue, lymph node biopsy, any body fluids (Pleural fluid, Ascitic fluid, Pericardial fluid, Peritoneal fluid, Urine), Endotracheal secretion, Bronchoalveolar lavage, Gastric lavage in paediatric patients should be collected in a sterile, leak-proof, screw capped universal container for the ultimate yield of the result. It has been estimated that, approximately 10,000 acid fast bacilli per ml. of sample are required to be detected by routine microscopy. Patients with extensive disease loaded with large numbers of Mycobacteria provides good correlation between positive smears to positive cultures, on the other hand, minimal or less advanced disease shows the correlation rate between 25-40%. Acid fast stain is also useful in prognosis. With detection of smear positivity, anti-tubercular treatment can be started at the earliest, besides with continued treatment more organisms are killed, so assessing the presence or absence of the organism during treatment can provide an early objective measure of response. The number of organisms fail to decrease after therapy is started, the possibility of drug resistance must be considered and additional culture and drug susceptibility studies should be required.

node.name: ACTIVE PROLACTIN
node.undefined6: active prolactin, cost of active prolactin, APROL,ACTIVE PROLACTIN
node.undefined8: Prolactin circulates in three forms ; monomeric prolactin which is the usual main form and is both biologically active and immunologically active. The other circulating forms of prolactin are heterogenous - big prolactin and big big prolactin or macro prolactin. They are present in varying quantities. These two forms result from the binding of monomeric prolactin toprolactin binding antibodies which have reduced or no biological activity as they cannot cross the capillary wall and have no clinical significance. Prolactin measurement is subjected to interference from high molecular weight variants including macroprolactin. Macroprolactin should be considered if there is elevated levels of prolactin but there are no symptoms. It can be a cause of misdiagnosis and of mismanagement of patient. All serum with increased prolactin with no symptoms should be tested for macro prolactin which can cross react in the assay. When corrected for macroprolactin, the active prolactin concentration for such patients is normal.

node.name: ACTIVE VITAMIN B12- HOLOTRANSCOBALAMIN
node.undefined6: active vitamin b12,active vitamin b12 test,ctive vitamin b12 blood test ,active vitamin b12 levels, AB12,ACTIVE VITAMIN B12- HOLOTRANSCOBALAMIN
node.undefined8:
Clinical Vitamin B 12 deficiency

Clinical vitamin B12 deficiency includes two main manifestations:

Hematologicaland/or Neuropsychiatric disorders The symptoms of early Vitamin B12 deficiency can often be missed as the symptoms of early deficiency are not very specific. 

Symptoms of Vitamin B12 deficiency can develop when the total Vitamin B12 is still within the laboratory reference range, therefore total Vitamin B12 level in the blood may not be indicative of true Vitamin B12 deficiency. 

It is a late marker of Vitamin  B12 deficiency.  Changes in the Total B12 result may not occur until the patient is already Vitamin B12 deficient. 

Measuring total Vitamin B12 can underestimate Vitamin B12 deficiency because the portion of Holotranscobalamin (HoloTC) within the total Vitamin B12 is not linear over the whole serum Vitamin B12 concentration range. This means that total Vitamin B12 concentrations may be within the reference range but the concentration of HoloTC may be low. Hence it is advisable not to rely only on serum Vit B12 levels alone for diagnosing Vit B12 deficiency. As Total B12 test suffers from a number of important limitations.

node.name: ADRENALINE (EPINEPHRINE) BY URINE
node.undefined6: adrenaline (epinephrine) by urine, ADREU, ADRENALINE (EPINEPHRINE) BY URINE
node.undefined8: Adrenaline (Epinephrine) by Urine Adrenaline is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands which rest on top of the kidneys. In case of any stress, this hormone is released in the blood and is responsible for increasing the heart rate, blood pressure, rate of breathing and increasing alertness. It redirects the blood flow towards the vital organs like brain, liver etc by diverting it from the periphery. This investigation is done when there is suspicion for any tumour that may secrete this hormone. Increased levels are commonly seen in pheochromocytoma (hormone secreting tumour of the adrenal gland) which is responsible for severe headaches, high blood pressure, palpitations, giddiness. This may be one of the reasons of high blood pressure in adults. Prior to performing (2-3 days) this test, it is important to refrain from certain food items and beverages like coffee, tea, soft drinks containing caffeine, chocolate, banana, avocados, walnuts, vanilla, cheese, beer, wine and licorice. Avoid smoking or chewing products containing tobacco during the entire collection process. Avoid strenuous exercise as well. Some drugs containing amphetamine like compounds, some allergy medicines, medicines for cold, appetite suppressants, dexamethasone, diuretics etc may affect the test results and may need to be discontinued for a week before this investigation is perfomed. Please inform your doctor about all the medications you are taking. Some physicians may also prescribe measurements of plasma / urine metanephrine and normetanephrines. These are metabolic products of epinephrine and nor epinephrine respectively.

node.name: ADRENOCORTICOTROPIC HORMONE, PLASMA
node.undefined6: adrenocorticotropic hormone plasma,adrenocorticotropic hormone test, ACTH,ADRENOCORTICOTROPIC HORMONE, PLASMA
node.undefined8: ACTH is a hormone released by the pituitary gland present in the brain. The ACTH signals the release of cortisol from the Adrenal glands in response to any stress in the body. ACTH is in turn controlled by a hormone Corticotropin Releasing Factor (CRF) released from the hypothalamus and an increase in cortisol reduces the ACTH levels by negative feedback mechanism ACTH along with cortisol levels is commonly used in the diagnosis of : ? Cushing Disease ? Hypopituitarism ? Addison Disease ? Cushing syndrome ? Ectopic tumour producing ACTH ? Secondary Adrenal Insufficiency ? Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia Cushing Disease: A hormone producing tumour of the pituitary gland will cause an increase in the ACTH levels which is turn will increase the cortisol levels as well. Hypopituitarism : Any disease of the pituitary gland by tumor/infection will result in reduced levels of ACTH. This may present with symptoms of Unexplained weight loss, loss of appetite, loss of sex drive, dysfunction of sex organs, increased urination, irregular menses and hot flashes. Cushing Syndrome : This disease is due to increase in the cortisol levels in the body, either due to a hormone producing tumour or excess corticosteroid received as medication. As a feedback, the increase in cortisol will signal the pituitary gland to reduce production of ACTH. Patients with excess cortisol levels present with symptoms of weight gain (mostly around the trunk), purple striae on abdomen, increase in blood pressure and blood sugar levels, diabetes, increase in facial / body hair and acne. Addison Disease : There are symptoms of muscle pain, weakness, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, salt cravings, weight loss due to reduced levels of cortisol , as a result of disease of the adrenal glands. As the cortisol reduces, there is a corresponding increase in ACTH levels . This is the body?s feedback mechanism trying to increase the cortisol levels by increasing the ACTH levels. Plasma ACTH show a lot of variation throughout the day and is highest in the early morning. The lowest values are seen in the evening. Cortisol levels are frequently measured at the same time as ACTH. An increased level of ACTH means that the person may have Cushings Disease, Addisons Disease or tumour producing ACTH A decreased ACTH level is seen in hypopituitarism, Disease of the hypothalamus, excess of cortisol due to adrenal tumour or corticosteroid medications. node.undefined8: This test is advised by clinicians to detect presence of microorganism in blood, a condition commonly knowns as bacteremia or septicaemia(Sepsis). Sepsis is manifested as fever, chills malaise. Sepsis if left untreated can be life threating, thus timely diagnosis is important. This test can detect bacterial as well as fungi like candida infection in blood . Blood culture in our lab is carried out by an automated machine, BACT/ALERT 3D, which is designed to detect growth of bacteria as they multiply and grow in the blood culture bottle. The System is based on a calorimetric detection of growth which is reflected as a colour change in a pH sensitive sensor at the base of the bottle. How the test is performed - Patients blood sample is taken into the culture bottles and incubated in the BACT/ALERT 3D machine. If microorganism grows, the machine will give a signal. Further the microorganism is identified and tested for susceptibility against different antibiotics to help guide the treatment. Positive results means microorganism has been detected in the given blood sample. Negative result means no microorganism was isolated in vitro.

node.name: AIR SURVEILLANCE
node.undefined6: air surveillance, AIRS,AIR SURVEILLANCE
node.undefined8: It is a test carried out to know the bacterial load in environment. Monitoring the presence of microorganisms in air is important in hospitals, especially operation theatres, tissue culture laboratories. This test is done with use of Air Sampler uni(instrument). It is based on impaction principle. The air under examination is sucked in the instrument and air particles are centrifugally impacted against the inward facing peripheral Agar medium strip as the spiralling return air escapes . Then the agar strips are incubated for 48 hours and observed for growth of microorganism colony. Colony counts are informed to the respective hospital/institutes wheather the air in the given place has permissible bacterial air load or not.

node.name: ALDOSTERONE
node.undefined6: aldosterone,aldosterone blood test, test aldosterone, aldosterone level test, aldosterone serum, aldosterone test, ALDO,ALDOSTERONE,congenital adrenal hyperplasia profile
node.undefined8: Aldosterone is a hormone produced by the adrenal gland and plays and important role in regulation of water, sodium and potassium in the body. Aldosterone production is stimulated by the hormone Renin produced by the Kidneys. The aldosterone primary function is to retain water and sodium from the kidney while allowing potassium to pass in the urine. This results in increase in blood volume and blood pressure. Aldosterone is ordered by the clinician when there is suspicion for increase or decrease of its levels. Aldosterone is increased in : ? Primary Aldosteronism ? Secondary Aldosteronism ? Barter Syndrome ? Pregnancy ? Very Low sodium Diets Primary Aldosteronism: This is caused by increased production of Aldosterone by the adrenal glands usually by a benign tumour. Increase in aldosterone results in increased salt and water absorption and increased excretion of potassium from the kidneys, which in turn increases the blood pressure and produces symptoms of headache, palpitations, giddiness and muscle weakness. Secondary Aldosteronism : In this case, the increase in Aldosterone is due to an increase in the Renin. Commonly caused by reduced blood supply to the kidneys due to stenosis of the renal arteries, this condition reduce the blood flow to the kidneys which result in increase renin secretion. This is turn increases the Aldosterone levels and increases the blood pressure. This condition can be treated and can cure the hypertension as a result. Aldosterone is decreased in: ? Hyporenenemic aldosteronism ? Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia ? Deficiency of Aldosterone Synthethase ? Addison Disease ? Very High Sodium Diets Aldosterone levels may be affected by the salt in the diet as well as certain drugs like NSAIDS, diuretics, ACE inhibitors which may be used to control high blood pressure. "

In such cases if the wound is left unattended may lead gangrene of leg and further amputation. Thus anaerobic culture test is advised in such clinical scenario. Test procedure ? Gram staining is done with culture of these sample. Cultures are incubated under anaerobic conditions. Reports are released as Prelim report at the end of 72 hrs and final 7 days. ACE is used in the body to convert Angiotensin1 to Angiotensin 2. Angiotensin 2 in turn, stimulates the adrenal gland to secrete aldosterone . Aldosterone acts to retain salt and water in the body and get rid of potassium. This increases the blood volume and blood pressure. This enzyme (ACE) is the target for the class of drugs called ACE inhibitors, which helps reduce blood pressure by inhibiting ACE
ACE is also used for diagnosis of Sarcoidosis. Sarcoidosis is a disease where there is presence of nodules called granulomas throughout the body. There are seen in sites like lung, skin, intestine etc and are part of the differential diagnosis of diseases causing granulomatous inflammation.
Patient with sarcoidosis present with chronic cough, breathlessness, redness and watering of eyes and joint pains. This disease is usually seen in adults between 20 to 40 years of age. ACE levels are increased in about 50% to 70% of patients with active disease however is seen in only 11% patients with inactive disease.
ACE levels are also used to follow the disease activity, with increase in levels correlating with increased disease activity and decrease in ACE levels correlating with reduced disease activity.
ACE levels are also increased in: ? Diabetes Mellitus ? Hyperthyroidism ? Leprosy ? Cirrhosis ? Silicosis ? Amyloidosis ? TB infection
ACE levels may be decreased in : ? Lung disease like COPD ? Anorexia associated with Hypothyroidism ? Steroid therapy "

node.undefined8: Measles is a highly contagious infection caused by Measles virus (a paramyxovirus). It presents with respiratory and mucocutaneous symptoms like fever, cough, malaise, nasal discharge, conjunctivitis, oral ulcerative lesions and generalized reddish maculopapular rash. Complications include high morbidity and mortality due to accompanying pneumonia, impaired nutrition and meningoencephalitis. Specific IgG antibody production starts 1?2 weeks after initial infection, reaches a peak level at 4?8 weeks, and later declines to a detectable low titres for lifelong. Natural infection with measles presumably provides lifelong immunity against re-infection. This test is done to determine immune status, diagnose active infection and detect, monitor and track measles outbreaks for public health purposes. Measles IgG antibody testing is done by ELISA method. Positive test indicates immunity against measles following vaccination or previous infection. Patient with active/acute infection shows fourfold rise in antibody titre in sera collected during acute phase and 10-21 days later. Negative test result means person is non-immune to the virus. Measles IgG antibody test is usually ordered along with measles IgM antibody for better correlation of results.

node.name: BETA 2 GLYCOPROTEIN I IGM
node.undefined6: beta-2 glycoprotein i igm,beta-2 glycoprotein ab igm,beta 2 glycoprotein antibodies igm, beta 2 glycoprotein igm test,BETA 2 GLYCOPROTEIN I IGM
node.undefined8: This test is ordered when the clinicians suspects the presence of Antiphospholipid syndrome (APS) or other autoimmune disorders like Systemic Lupus Erythomatosis (SLE). It should be suspected in patient with symptoms of abnormal clotting or cases of recurrent miscarriages. Beta 2 Glycoprotein is one of the antiphospholipid antibodies which are usually ordered with other antibodies like Cardiolipin antibody and Lupus Anticoagulant. Patients with APS may present with abnormal clotting in body that may result in: ? Pain the extremity ? Chest pain ? Difficulty in Breathing ? Headache ? Stroke ? Seizure ? Memory loss ? Pregnancy complications like recurrent miscarriages or pre-eclampsia The presence of Beta 2 Glycoprotein antibodies (IgM and IgG) is not diagnostic for APS. They may be present temporarily at the time of testing, in case of acute infection. To confirm their presence, the patients should be retested after 12 weeks and should also have clinical symptoms of APS. Absence of Beta 2 glycoprotein does not rule of APS. Test should be done for other antiphospholipid antibodies like Cardiolipin Antibodies, Lupus Anticoagulant and other less common antibodies like Anti Phosphatidylserine antibodies and Anti Prothrombin Antibodies. The presence of Beta 2 Glycoprotein along with other autoimmune diseases like SLE increases the chances of developing abnormal clotting in the body. It is possible for the patient to have coexisting APS along with lupus.

node.undefined8: Bile acids are formed from cholesterol in the liver , then conjugated , stored and finally concentrated in the gall bladder. After a meal, they are secreted into the intestine where they promote digestion of fatty food. During this phase almost 90% of the bile acids are reabsorbed. Usually, the bile acid clearance in the liver from the blood is quite efficient and hence the levels are quite low. If there is liver disease, the bile acid clearance is affected and hence the levels can increase. Cirrhosis, hepatitis, thrombosis of the portal vein, hemochromatosis etc can cause an increase in the bile acids.

node.undefined8: This test is used in patients with suspected brucellosis, a bacterial infection caused by Gram negative bacilli. This is usually transmitted via infected animals either by direct contact or by milk ingestion. Signs and symptoms include anorexia, fever , chills , weakness, headache, fatigue, lethargy and night sweats. Lymph nodes might be enlarged. The antibody test is an additional test to culture. It takes 1-2 weeks after the onset of symptoms for the test to become positive. A 4 fold increase is titre is ideally used to diagnose acute infections. The gold standard still remains identifying the organism from the marrow, body fluids or tissue specimens. One important fact to remember is that a single positive test is not enough to signify an acute infection since antibodies may remain in the blood for months to years.

node.undefined8: Brucellosis is a gram negative bacterial infection caused by Brucella species. Human beings are infected by intake of unpasteurized milk and its products, direct contact with infected material or inhalation of airborne agents. Bacteria mainly affect the reticuloendothelial system and causes disease in acute and chronic forms. Infection begins with fever, chills, malaise, headache, night sweats and other non-specific symptoms. In later stages it causes multiple abscesses in liver, spleen, kidney and brain. It is an occupational disease seen in people having close contact with animals (veterinary, butchers and livestock workers). Brucella IgG antibody test is done when patient is suspicious of having acute or chronic brucellosis. It is a screening test done by ELISA method. In acute infection, testing of paired sera few weeks apart helps in diagnosis. If test is positive, further confirmation is needed by specific agglutination assays. Usually IgG titres reduces after acute infection but can still be found in large amounts in non-symptomatic individuals. Chronic infection shows predominance of specific IgG antibody.

node.undefined8: This test is used to diagnose hereditary angioedema This measures an inhibitor which is usually found in the body in the plasma and serum. It regulates steps of multiple pathways including complement,fibrinolytic, and kinin forming pathways. There are 2 major forms of deficiency , congenital and acquired. The congenital form is called hereditary angioedema(HAE). If the levels are very low, a congenital form is suspected. If a low value is present, repeat sampling and testing is advisable for confirmation since the assay is functional. CATECHOLAMINES The primary catecholamines are hormones such as Dopamine,epinephrine and norepinephrine. Pheochromocytomas produce these in excess. The primary test for this disorder is plasma free metanephrines and urine metanephrines. If these tests are inconclusive, then urinary testing for catecholamines is usually preferred over blood since it is more reliable. This test is usually ordered in a young patient with hypertension not responding to treatment along with severe headaches, sweating, flushing etc. It can also be used in an asymptomatic person with an incidentally detected mass on a CT scan. A positive test means that further investigation is needed. The total amount of catecholamines increases with the size of the tumor but is not related to the location of the tumor.

node.undefined8: Calprotectin is a stool (fecal) test, used to detect inflammation in the intestines. Intestinal inflammation is associated with someÂ bacterial infections and, in people withÂ Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), it is associated with disease activity and severity. The calprotectin test may be used to distinguish between IBD and non-inflammatory bowel disorders and to monitor the severity of IBD. A clinician may order a calprotectin test to help investigate the cause of a person's persistent watery or bloodyÂ diarrhoea. Testing is performed to determine what is causing a person's symptoms and to rule out conditions with similar symptoms. A calprotectin test may be ordered to help determine whether an endoscopy is indicated if IBD is suspected. A diagnosis of IBD is usually confirmed by performing an endoscopy (colonoscopy or sigmoidoscopy) to examine the intestines and by obtaining a small tissue sample (biopsy) to evaluate for inflammation and changes in tissue structures. This testing is invasive and is less likely to be necessary if inflammation is not present. A calprotectin test may be ordered if a person with IBD has symptoms that suggest a flare-up, both to detect disease activity and to help evaluate its severity. Increases in calprotectin are seen withÂ IBD, but also withÂ bacterialÂ infections, someÂ parasiticÂ infections and withÂ colorectal cancer.

node.undefined8: PCR is one of the best methods for a qualitative diagnosis of CMV. CMV is an opportunistic infection which takes place usually in the first year of organ transplant after the antiviral medications are halted. The patient usually presents with fever, low WBC count, hepatitis, colitis and retinal infections. The risk is highest when a CMV seronegative recipient receives a transplant from a CMV seropositive donors. The infection is usually present in the latent state in the donor organ and will be reactivated during a state of immunosupression in the recipient . A positive CMV PCR is usually followed by the quantification of the viral load. This is used to decide when to start anti viral treatment and monitor it?s response as well. Higher levels are associated with more invasive disease though this is not always the case. Weekly monitoring is advised. A change of >0.5 log IU/ml is considered significant.

node.undefined8: Digoxin is a drug that is used in treatment of Congestive Heart Failure and Atrial Fibrillation / Flutter ( a condition where the heart rate is very high). The test is ordered to determine whether the drug is in the therapeutic range to be effective or whether the patients symptoms are due to toxicity of digoxin. Toxicity is usually seen at levels more than 2.5 ng/ml, however in some patients it can be seen even above 2 ng/ml The likelihood of toxicity increases when other conditions are also present like low blood potassium, low magnesium, increased calcium levels, hypoxia and heart failure. Symptoms of digoxin toxicity may include ? Dizziness ? Vomiting ? Diarrhoea ? Blurred vision ? Seeing yellow or green halos ? Irregular heart beats ? Anorexia ? Difficulty in breathing Digoxin toxicity may increase with the co-administration of the following drugs ? Quinidine ? Verapamil ? Amiodarone ? Indomethacin ? Cyclosporin False low levels of digoxin may be seen due to the the drug - spironolactone

node.undefined8: Blood sugar is the measurement of Glucose in blood. Glucose comes from the carbohydrate foods and is the main source of energy used by the body. The level of Glucose is maintained by Insulin and Glucagon hormones. The normal range is- Fasting- 70-100 mg/dL, Post Lunch (Also known as Post Prandial-PP) - <140 mg/dL. Any values <70 mg/dL are termed as Hypoglycemia or Low Blood Sugar levels. and values >126 mg/dL for fasting, and >140 mg/dL for PP are termed as hyperglycemia, commonly known as Diabetes Mallitus (DM). Values between 101 to 125 for Fasting are termed as Impaired Glucose Tolerance, and are further advised investigations, specially GTT, to confirm the diagnosis of DM. Blood sugar tests are done to Diagnose DM and hypoglycemia, to moniter the treatment for DM, diagnose Pancreatic disorders, endocrine disorders, certain CNS lesions, Drdugs etc.

node.name: ESTIMATION OF CORTISOL,SERUM
node.undefined6: estimation of serum cortisol,serum cortisol estimation, cost of cortisol estimation, CORTI, corti,ESTIMATION OF CORTISOL,SERUM
node.undefined8: Cortisol is an important hormone released from the adrenal gland. It affects the metabolism of protein, fat and carbohydrates. It plays an important role in suppressing inflammation and allergic reactions in the body. A high or low serum cortisol levels can result in several biochemical and metabolic abnormalities. This test is frequently ordered along with serum ACTH to determine the source of increase or decrease of cortisol i.e. whether it is due to primary involvement of the adrenal gland or secondary to changes in ACTH (released from the pituitary gland). Increase in serum cortisol can result in: Cushing Syndrome: This disease is due to increase in the cortisol levels in the body, either due to a hormone producing tumour or excess corticosteroid received as medication. As a feedback, the increase in cortisol will signal the pituitary gland to reduce production of ACTH. Patients with excess cortisol levels present with symptoms of weight gain (mostly around the trunk), purple striae on abdomen, increase in blood pressure and blood sugar levels, diabetes, increase in facial / body hair and acne. Low levels of cortisol can be as a result of: Addison Disease: There are symptoms of muscle pain, weakness, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, salt cravings, weight loss due to reduced levels of cortisol, as a result of disease of the adrenal glands. As the cortisol reduces, there is a corresponding increase in ACTH levels. This is the body?s feedback mechanism trying to increase the cortisol levels by increasing the ACTH levels. There is significant variation in secretion of cortisol throughout the day. For this purpose, it?s important to note the time of blood collection for appropriate reference ranges.

node.undefined6: estimation of c-peptide, c-peptide fasting serum, CPEPT, cpept,ESTIMATION OF C-PEPTIDE
node.undefined8:
C Peptide is produced in the pancreas when proinsulin is split to insulin and C peptide. Therefore, C peptide levels correlate with the amount of insulin produced by the pancreas. Increase levels of C peptide are seen in conditions with increased pancreatic beta cell activity, whereas reduced levels are seen in condition where the pancreatic beta cells are destroyed or are non-functional.
This makes it a useful marker to differentiate between Type 1 and Type 2 diabetes, as well as to identify low blood sugar levels due to exogenously administered insulin.
C peptide levels are increased in Type 2 Diabetes and Insulin producing tumour of the pancreas (Insulinoma)
C peptide levels are reduced in Type 1 Diabetes and Exogenous insulin administration.

These women may present with irregular menses, weight gain, excessive facial and body hair. node.undefined6: estimation of estradiol, ESTRA , estrogen, estradiol, ESTRA, estra,ESTIMATION OF ESTRADIOL.
node.undefined8: Estradiol (E2) is one of the most active endogenous estrogens produced in the body. They are commonly ordered to detect conditions that may occur due to excess or decreased production. It is commonly ordered in conjunction with other hormones in women who have issues with fertility and/or menstrual irregularities like amenorrhoea. High levels of estradiol maybe seen in girls with precious puberty, where they develop secondary sexual characteristics before puberty. High levels may also be seen in certain estrogen producing tumours. Estradiol is also monitored in women undergoing in-vitro fertilisation (IVF) cycles, to correlate if the ovarian follicle is secreting sufficient estrogen, indirectly indicating good ovarian follicle health. It is also used to monitor hormone replacement therapy in menopausal women In men, high levels of estradiol maybe associated with gynaecomastia. Or delayed puberty. High levels maybe seen in estrogen producing tumours as well. Certain conditions like hyperthyroidism or liver cirrhosis may increase estradiol levels in both men and women. Reduced levels of estradiol may be seen in primary or secondary hypogonadism where the ovaries secrete less estrogen either due disease in the ovaries themselves are due to reduction in stimulating hormones.

node.name: ESTIMATION OF FREE P.S.A.
node.undefined6: estimation of free p.s.a, FPSA, fpsa,ESTIMATION OF FREE P.S.A.
node.undefined8: PSA circulates in the body in two forms one as PSA bound to the protein and the other as an unbound state called Free PSA. The free PSA measures the percentage of unbound form, which is not bound to any protein and circulates as it is. Whereas PSA measures total PSA both bound and unbound free PSA. In Prostate cancer, PSA increses but not all elevated PSA levels are due to malignancy. There are other benign conditions also in which PSA increases like prostatis, benign prostate hyperplasia, trauma, urinary tract infections, pressure on the prostate when riding a motorcycle or bicycle, ejaculation, etc. In fact 75% of all elevated PSA do not have malignancy. Whenever PSA level is between 4 ? 10 ng/dl which is the gray zone in diagnosing, along with PSA, Free PSA is also done.Higher the PSA and lower the Free PSA greater are the chances of having malignancy. Hence the ratio of free PSA to total PSA is a better indicator of prostate malignancy.

node.undefined8: Thyroid gland produces hormones called tri-iodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4). T3 is the active form of T4. These hormones play an important role in growth and development of tissues and regulating heart rate, basal metabolism and temperature of the body. Majority of the T3 in circulation is reversibly bound to carrier proteins. Unbound form is called as free T3. Thyroid disorders are the commonest endocrine abnormalities seen in the clinical practice. Free T3 test is carried out to assess thyroid gland functioning. Free T3 is not affected by serum protein levels and tends to remain more constant. Hence it is gives a more true value of thyroid status in conditions having altered proteins levels (pregnancy, intake of oral contraceptive pills and nephrotic syndrome). Measurement of Free T3 is done by CMIA technique. It is usually measured along with free T4 and TSH. This test helps in early diagnosis of hyperthyroidism which has an elevated free T3 levels but normal free T4 levels. Low levels of T3 indicate in hypothyroid state. Final interpretation of this test needs to be done after correlating with TSH levels and patients clinical condition.

node.undefined8: It is a hormone secreted by pituitary gland. The main role of Prolactin is stimulation of milk production. It can be increased physiologically as well as pathologically. Physiologically it can increase in stress, seizures, pregnancy, lactation, breast stimulation, sexual intercourse, exercise. Other medical conditions in which it can be increased is a tumour in pituitary gland, primary hypothyroidism and other conditions. Dopamine inhibits secretion of prolactin whereas TSH stimulates its secretion. Prolactin circulates in three forms ; monomeric prolactin which is the usual main form and is both biologically active and immunologically active. The other forms of prolactin are heterogenous - big prolactin and big big prolactin or macro prolactin. These two forms result from the binding of monomeric prolactin toprolactin binding antibodies which have reduced or no biological activity as they cannot cross the capillary wall and have no clinical significance. Prolactin measurement is subjected to interference from high molecular weight variants including macroprolactin. Macroprolactin should be considered if there is elevated levels of prolactin but there are no symptoms. It can be a cause of misdiagnosis and of mismanagement of patient.

node.undefined8: Testosterone circulates in the blood bound to certain proteins like Sex Hormone Binding Globulin (SHBG), albumin and cortisol. Only 2% to 3% of testosterone is present in the free state.It is considered that testosterone bound to SHBG is not available for action in the tissues whereas testosterone bound to albumin and free testosterone is the fraction that is available for acting on tissues.Measuring total testosterone therefore measures all bound and unbound form and to a large extent depends on the concentration of SHBG to which it is most commonly bound (approx.. 44% of testosterone is bound to SHBG).SHBG concentration, however, is affected by many factors. It is decreased in Obesity, testosterone treatment, Polycystic ovarian Syndrome and increased in aging, pregnancy, estrogen therapy. In these conditions, additionally testing free testosterone may be helpful.Increased production of testosterone in childhood may lead to precocious/early puberty in males and masculinization in girls. In adult women increased testosterone may result in irregular or absence of menses, increased facial/body hair and acne. Increased production of testosterone could be because of adrenal, ovarian or testicular tumours producing this hormone or due to a genetic condition resulting in hyperplasia of the adrenal glands (congenital adrenal hyperplasia). Increased levels may also be seen in athletes who may use gonadotropins to increase testosterone production. Decreased levels of testosterone in females may lead to reduced sex drive or non-specific mood changes. In males, it may be lead to change on male sexual characteristics, infertility and loss of sex drive. Reduced testosterone levels may be due to primary failure of the testes/ovaries or a consequence of reduced secretion of stimulating hormones from the pituitary/hypothalamus.

node.undefined6: galactomannan, serum, galactomannan serum test, cost of galactomannan serum test,1728,GALACTOMANNAN, SERUM
node.undefined8: It is used in suspected cases of invasive aspergillosis This infection usually takes place in patients whose immune status is compromised due to various reason for a length of time. This can happen in transplants, chemotherapy and is seen when the blood WBC count falls for an extended period of time. It is a serious illness with high mortality rates. A histopathology specimen is an ideal sample but in many cases this is not feasible. Serum galactomannan is a antigen found in the cell wall of the Aspergillus species. It is a serological test which can come positive 7-14 days before other diagnostic tests\signs or symptoms come positive. Anti fungal treatment can be initiated on the basis of this result. A positive test supports the diagnosis of invasive aspergillosis but must be considered along with other diagnostic procedures such as culture, histopathology and CT scans. A negative result does not rule of Invasive aspergillosis and must be repeated if the clinical suspicion is strong. If a test is positive, the test must be repeated with a new specimen since false positive reports are known. False positive results are seen with the use of antibiotics based on the genus penicillium.

node.name: GAMMA INTERFERON TEST FOR TB
node.undefined6: gamma interferon test for tb, interferon gamma release assay test for tb,interferon gamma blood test for tb, interferon gamma testing in tb, interferon gamma for diagnosis of tuberculosis, GITB, gitb,GAMMA INTERFERON TEST FOR TB
node.undefined8:
Gamma Interferon test also known as Interferon Gamma Release Assays (IGRA) is a test done on the blood of patient who is suspected to have tuberculosis. This tests aids in the diagnosis of tuberculosis. However, it does not differentiate latent infection from active infections.
Those individuals who have been exposed to the Mycobacterium tuberculosis bacteria show an immune response when their T lymphocytes are mixed with certain tuberculous antigen. These lymphocytes release interferon gamma which is measured. A positive test suggests that infection with Mycobacterium tuberculosis is likely and if negative means that it is unlikely. However, this test is only meant as an aid in diagnosis and not for confirmation of diagnosis. Prior vaccination with BCG does not give a false positive result. However, this test cannot predict which individuals will go on to develop tuberculosis in the future.

node.undefined8: Genexpert is a multiplex, rapid, real-time DNA-PCR technique. It is a revolution in the detection of TB infection. Whether AFB smear and Chest Xray are used as screening tests for the diagnosis, Genexpert is used for the diagnosis of Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection along with Rifampicin susceptible or resistance. Rifampicin resistance indicates the infection is MDR (Multi-drug resistance) the treatment protocol of which is different from Primary Tuberculosis infection treatment. The culture is gold standard for the diagnosis but it takes too long time (6-8 weeks). And early initiation of treatment is the key. In this aspect Genexpert plays an important role as it gives the diagnosis in a day to detect TB infection along with MDR pattern. The sensitivity and specificity of the test is 97% and 98.3% respectively. Thus, it is extremely helpful in the diagnosis in smear negative cases of infection. Sputum, Bronchoalveolar lavage, Endotracheal secretion, Pleural fluid, Peritoneal fluid, Pericardial fluid, Ascitic fluid, Synovial fluid, Aspirated pus, tissue, endometrium, Lymph node biopsy samples can be processed in this test. Thus, it is very useful for the diagnosis of pulmonary as well as extra-pulmonary infection. Urine, stool and blood-stained samples processing is contraindicated. So, for the confirmation of diagnosis of Tuberculosis with multi-drug resistance pattern Genexpert is a first-line diagnostic modality.

Samples are inoculated on Special media for gonococci also Gram stain of the sample is done which can give clue to presence of gonococci in the given sample. Culture media are incubated under standard condition upto 72 hours and observed daily for growth of microorganism Neisseria gonorrhoeae. If growth detected they are further identified by various test. If growth not detected culture media afre incubated upto 72 hrs before giving No growth report.

node.undefined6: hain mtbdrplus 1st line drug susceptibility lpa, cost of hain mtbdrplus 1st line drug susceptibility lpa, HAIN1,hain1,HAIN MTBDRPLUS 1ST LINE DRUG SUSCEPTIBILITY (LPA)
node.undefined8: HAIN is the Line probe assay, DNA-based molecular test. The novel diagnostic test - called MTBDRplus is a multiplex PCR based on DNA-strip technology that identifies genetic mutations in TB strains, making them resistant to isoniazid and rifampicin. It is the first rapid genetic assay approved by WHO used for anti-Mycobacterial drugs susceptibility test. MTBDRplus (HAIN first line) is used to detect Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex directly and isoniazid and rifampicin susceptibility to it, which is very helpful to diagnose MDR tuberculosis in a very short period of time. Resistance to rifampicin is a critical pre-requisite for identifying patients who can be put on second line anti-TB regimen. It is fully automated amplification and detection technique allowing reliable nucleic acid extraction from different sample materials. It is suitable and economical for low, mid and high throughput, one single platform for direct detection, drug susceptibility testing and differentiation. According to WHO recommendations it is used for the direct testing of sputum specimens as well as indirect testing on culture isolates from rifampicin-resistant or MDR-TB patients, including adults and children (irrespective of the smear status). It does not eliminate the need for phenotypic DST to confirm resistance to other drugs and to monitor the emergence of additional drug resistance during treatment.

node.undefined6: haptoglobin, haptoglobin level, haptoglobin test, haptoglobin blood test, cost of haptoglobin blood test, HEPTO,HAPTOGLOBIN
node.undefined8: RBCs break down in haemolytic states to release haemoglobin in the plasma. Haptoglobin, which is a plasma protein binds to Hb and forms a complex. This complex is removed from the plasma by macrophages. This process continues till the binding capacity of haptoglobin is exhausted after which Hb is excreted in the urine. Therefore, if Hemolysis continues for an extended period of time, then the serum haptoglobin level will be low. One must keep in mind that the serum haptoglobin level can be low in strenuous exercise as well as in severe liver disorders. Haptoglobin is an acute phase reactant and can increase in cases of inflammation In the first 3-6 months of life, a low level of haptoglobin is normal

node.undefined8: H. Pylori is a bacterium that colonizes the stomach mucous lining and makes it more susceptible to the effects of gastric acid. This results in patients developing gastritis, peptic ulcers and in some long-term cases, gastric carcinoma. To detect the presence of infections, IgG and IgA antibodies produced by the immune systems are detected. A positive IgG test may be seen in individuals with recent or past infection with H.Pylori and does not differentiate between the two. However, those with a negative test are unlikely to have H. Pylori infection. Some patients may develop IgA antibodies in addition to IgG antibodies. IgA may not be present in all infected with H.pylori and is commonly added as an additional follow up investigation after IgG. Antibody concentrations reduce after treatment but are still detectable. Hence, they are not used after treatment begins, for test of cure. Other ways to identify H. Pylori infection include Urease Breath test and Stool antigen test. These tests don?t depend on the persons immune system and can be used to detect current infection as well as for the evaluation of effectiveness of treatment. They are usually ordered if the antibody tests are positive and to monitor effectiveness of therapy.

node.name: HIGH SENSITIVE TROPONIN - I
node.undefined6: high sensitive troponin I, Tropihs, TROPiHS,HIGH SENSITIVE TROPONIN - I
node.undefined8: Troponin I is a protein that is specifically present in the heart muscles and help in the interaction of heart muscle filaments that are responsible for contraction. Troponin I is most commonly used for the diagnosis of Myocardial Infarction ( Heart attack) and is an important marker for irreversible cardiac muscle death/injury. Troponin I levels may be elevated, even when there are no ECG changes and the other cardiac enzymes are non diagnostic. Troponin I is one the earliest cardiac marker to increase (~ 4 to 6hrs), after FABP and Myoglobin, in case of a heart attack. It may take up to 12 hours for all patients to show an increase in Troponin I and remains elevated for approximately 9-10 days after a heart attack. High Sensitivity Troponin I measures very small amounts of Troponin I in the blood stream. Serial Monitoring of these levels can help rule in or rule out a heart attack. Troponin I does not increase in skeletal muscle injury which makes it a more specific cardiac marker as compared to troponin T or CKMB. Troponin I may also be increased in other conditions like mycocarditis (inflammation of the heart muscles), congestive heart failure and cardiomyopathy. Any damage to the heart muscle will result in increase in Troponin I levels in the blood.

node.name: HOMA INDEX INSULIN RESISTANCE TEST
node.undefined6: homa index insulin resistance test,HOMAIR,HOMA INDEX INSULIN RESISTANCE TEST
node.undefined8: This test is done to assess insulin resistance and beta cell function (of pancreas). Insulin resistance is seen in many conditions like Type 2 Diabetes, Hypertension, Dyslipedemia, PCOS etc. Insulin resistance causes decreased uptake of glucose by fat and muscle, decreased glycogen formation and increased liver glucose production. HOMA is a calculated value and the algorithm uses glucose fasting and insulin levels ( c peptide in case patient is a diabetic and is on insulin). The advantage of HOMA over other tests like OGTT is that it is less invasive as compared to OGTT where 5 times the blood is taken. The feedback loop between the liver and beta cells is central to the model. Plasma glucose concentration in the basal state is regulated by hepatic glucose output which is insulin dependent. Insulin concentration is dependent on beta cell response to glucose. Insulin signals glucose uptake in fat and muscle. Glucose disposal is modeled in brain and kidney as being dependent only on glucose, and in fat and muscle as being dependent on glucose and insulin concentration.

node.undefined6: identification of mycobacteria- hain's, HAIND,IDENTIFICATION OF MYCOBACTERIA- HAIN'S
node.undefined8: HAIN is line probe assay, a DNA-based molecular test. The novel diagnostic test is a multiplex PCR based on DNA-strip technology that identifies Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex and different atypical non-Tuberculous Mycobacteria (NTM) in a very short period of time. It is the first rapid genetic assay approved by WHO used for identification of various Mycobacterial species. It includes Mycobacterium CM and Mycobacterium AS panel. Mycobacterium CM panel gives identification of 27 species of Mycobacterium species and Mycobacterium AS panel gives identification of 19 Mycobacterium species which covers wide range of identification of Mycobacterium species including Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex and other non-Tuberculous Mycobacteria (NTM). As the treatment protocol is completely different from Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex treatment, it is very important to know the diagnosis of atypical mycobacteria which is responsible for Mycobacterium infection with a completely different clinical set up. It is a fully automated amplification and detection technique allowing reliable nucleic acid extraction from culture only. It is suitable and economical for low, mid and high throughput, one single platform for direct detection of Mycobacterium species.

node.undefined8: Insulin-Like Growth Factor 1 (IGF-1) is a hormone that is similar in structure to insulin and works in conjunction with Growth hormone to reproduce and regenerate cells. Growth Hormone, made by the pituitary gland, stimulates the liver to produce IGF-1 and IGF-1 subsequently stimulates growth in cells throughout the body, leading to growth and development (as in the womb and through adolescence), strengthening of tissues (improving bone density, building muscle), and healing (skin, bones, gut lining, etc.), depending on what the body needs. IGF-1 is so crucial to development that if it is not present in adequate amounts during the time when a child is developing, a short stature may result. It was formerly called Somatomedin. It is usually tested with Growth hormone. IGF-1 mirrors GH excesses and deficiencies, but the level in the blood is stable throughout the day, making it a useful indicator of average GH levels. Elevated levels of IGF1 may indicate elevated levels of Growth hormone too. An IGF-1 may be tested when there is a suspicion of an underactive pituitary gland and it is also tested at intervals to monitor those on GH therapy.

node.undefined8: Inhibin A is done in Quaduple marker test (second trimester) along with bhcg, AFP, unconjugated estriol, to find out the risk for chromosomal abnormality. In females, inhibin A is primarily produced by the dominant follicle and corpus luteum. Serum inhibin A levels fluctuate during the menstrual cycle. At menopause, with the depletion of ovarian follicles, serum inhibin A decrease to very low or undetectable levels. Inhibin A is elevated in granulosa cell tumour and mucinous epitheloid tumour of ovary. The majority of the studies for inhibin A and B as an ovarian cancer marker have been limited to postmenopausal women where the levels for both proteins are normally very low. Inhibin A has limited utility as an ovarian cancer marker in premenopausal women, where circulating levels are higher and fluctuate during the cycle hence it is difficult to interpret. Inhibins are heterodimeric protein hormones secreted by granulosa cells of the ovary in the female and Sertoli cells of the testis in the male. They selectively suppress the secretion of pituitary follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and also have local paracrine actions in the gonads. The inhibins consist of a dimer of 2 homologous subunits, an alpha subunit and either a beta A or beta B subunit, to form inhibin A and inhibin B, respectively.

node.name: LITHIUM
node.undefined6: lithium, cost of lithium test, LITHI,LITHIUM
node.undefined8: Lithium is a drug used commonly for the treatment of bipolar disorder. This test measures the concentration of lithium in the blood. After starting therapy with lithium, the doctor may order the test sequentially to test if the drug is within the therapeutic range. The drug needs to be in the therapeutic range to be effective. If it is below the therapeutic range, it indicated that the patients requires a higher dose of lithium or needs to take his medication regularly, if not doing so. The usual therapeutic range is 0.6-1.2 mmol/L. If the drug levels are above the therapeutic range, the patient may experience symptoms due to lithium toxicity, such as drowsiness, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, confusion, tremors, restlessness, slurred speech and muscle weakness. These symptoms may also be present in few patients with blood lithium levels at the upper end of the therapeutic level. Lithium is excreted through the kidney and may affect kidney function in the long term. Thus, a watch has to be kept on the kidney function as well. node.name: MYCOBACT DRUG SUSCEPTIBILITY (L.J. METHOD)
node.undefined6: mycobact drug susceptibility -LJ method , cost of mycobact drug susceptibility LJ method, LJSD,MYCOBACT DRUG SUSCEPTIBILITY (L.J. METHOD)
node.undefined8: It is the anti-tubercular drug susceptibility testing for Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex by Lowenstein-Jensen Media. It is the low-cost test includes any single drug of first and second line anti-TB drugs and gold standard method for detecting susceptibility. It is based on 1% proportion method to determine the phenotypic susceptible/resistance of the organism to a particular drug. The proportion method determines the percentage of growth (number of colonies) of a defined inoculum on a drug-free control medium versus growth on culture media containing the critical concentration of an anti-TB drug. Thus, it includes internal quality control with ATCC Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex strain in each batch. It is recommended by RNTCP. In this method the critical concentration of the drug is determined at which the organism is susceptible or resistant. It is indirect method of detection which is done from pure culture of Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex isolated from different types of samples.

node.name: MYCOBACTERIAL CULTURE - BACT/ALERT 3D/MGIT SYSTEM
node.undefined6: mrapi,mycobacterial culture for tuberculosis diagnosis,Rapid culture for TB, culture for tuberculosis,cost of mycobacterial culture for tuberculosis diagnosis, MRAPI,MYCOBACTERIAL CULTURE - BACT/ALERT 3D/MGIT SYSTEM
node.undefined7: Prliminary Report - After 1 Week , Final - After 6 Weeks
node.undefined8: Tuberculosis continues to be a major health problem worldwide, affecting millions of people each year. Accurate and rapid diagnosis is key to controlling the disease. A rapid, sensitive and reliable fluorochrome based diagnostic method for detection of Mycobacterium species or Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex (MTC) is done by Liquid culture method (Middlebrook 7H9) as Liquid culture technique is more sensitive than solid culture method. In this method we use MGIT320 or BACT/ALERT system. It gives rapid, accurate diagnosis of Mycobacterium species or Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex. It includes growth supplements enhancing growth of Mycobacteria and additional antibiotic supplements which inhibits additional growth of contaminating bacteria which ensures the purity of mycobacteria. This method is recommended by both WHO and RNTCP. It has 15-20% more culture positivity rate in comparison with conventional L. J. solid culture method. All types of specimens, pulmonary as well as extra-pulmonary (except blood), can be inoculated into MGIT for primary isolation of mycobacteria. Specimens should be collected in clean, preferably sterile containers with a tight-fitted lid or cap. At least two morning specimens collected on separate days should be processed for each new case. For patients with respiratory symptoms, the specimens should be expectorated sputum and not saliva, with a volume of about 2-10 ml each. Specimens should be transported to the laboratory as quickly as possible. Delays in transportation, especially in hot weather, result in an increase in contaminating bacteria that result in higher contamination rate of the medium.

node.name: PARA THYROID HORMONE
node.undefined6: parathyroid hormone, parathyroid hormone function, parathyroid hormone test, c terminal parathyroid hormone, pth, PTH,PARA THYROID HORMONE
node.undefined8: Parathyroid hormone is secreted from the parathyroid gland located in the neck behind thyroid gland. Parathyroid hormone (PTH) regulates calcium levels in the blood, mainly by increasing the levels of calcium when they are too low.?It regulates calcium by its action on kidneys, bones and intestine Bones ??parathyroid hormone stimulates the release of calcium from large calcium stores in the bones into the bloodstream. This increases bone destruction and decreases the formation of new bone.?? Kidneys ??parathyroid hormone reduces loss of calcium in urine. Parathyroid hormone also stimulates the production of 125 dihydroxy Vit D in the kidneys. PTH increases the activity of 1-alpha hydroxylase enzyme, which converts 25-hydroxy Vit D, into 1,25-dihydroxy Vit D, the active form of Vit D, in the kidney. Intestine ??parathyroid hormone increases calcium absorption from food in the intestine, via its effects on vitamin D metabolism. When the calcium levels become low in our body, parathyroid gland produces more PTH . PTH in turn acts on the bones and releases calcium from its store into the blood stream. It also acts on kidneys and reduces the excretion of calcium in the urine. When the level of calcium increases in the blood, a negative feedback makes parathyroid gland stop PTH secretion.

node.name: PROCALCITONIN
node.undefined6: procalcitonin, procalcitonin test, procalcitonin blood test, procalcitonin assay, pcal1, PCAL1,PROCALCITONIN
node.undefined8: It is a precursor of Calcitonin. It is a marker of systemic infkammatory reponse to infection. In severe systemic inflammation particularly bacterial infections, procalcitonin is elevated. Its level is directly proportional to the inflammatory insult. Greater the inflammation greater will be the value. In a seriously ill patient, Procalcitonin is helpful in suggesting Sepsis or a systemic or severe bacterial infection. High levels of procalcitonin is also useful in telling whether it will progress to septic shock. By regular and serial procalcitonin estimation, It helps to decide whether antibiotics can be started or stopped for patients with sepsis and other conditions. Sepsis is the most common cause of death in non coronary ICU. Hence the importance of Procalcitonin It also distinguishes between bacterial and non bacterial causes of infections such as meningitis and pneumonia. In severe viral infections or in inflammatory conditions of non infectious origin , procalcitonin does not increase or is only little elevated Procalcitonin is very useful in diagnosing bacteremia in neonates and has an important role to play in children with urinary tract infections ? whether kidney involvement is there or not. Other tests which can be done with procalcitonin are CRP, Cultures ( blood and urine), Lactate etc. Hence procalcitonin is always interpreted with other tests and clinical findings

node.undefined8: MGIT stands for Mycobacteria Growth Indicator Tube. It is a system that determines whether or not TB bacteria will grow in the presence of TB drugs. If the bacteria grow, then they are resistant to the drugs, if the bacteria don't grow, the TB drugs work i.e. it is susceptible. In this case. It is a so-called liquid culture system using modified Middlebrook 7H9 broth. It contains growth supplements which enhances the growth of Tubercle bacilli and additional supplements to supress the growth of contaminating bacteria. And the system is based on fluoro-quenching technology. Liquid culture systems are currently the standard for drug susceptibility testing in industrialised countries. WHO have recommended liquid culture systems for low and middle-income countries as well. The advantage of liquid culture systems is that the bacteria grow much faster. So, it can determine much faster whether or not a TB bacterium grows in the culture, meaning whether or not that TB bacterium is susceptible to the TB drugs. This means that patients can receive the correct drugs faster and be treated in an efficient and timely way. We have 13 anti-TB drugs panel in it including both first and second line drugs. Thus, it helps to detect MDR-XDR TB in a faster way.

node.name: RUBELLA ( GERMAN MEASLES ) AVIDITY TEST
node.undefined6: rubella avidity test, rubella igg avidity test, rubella igm avidity test, avidity test for rubella, rubella german measles avidity test , ruba, RUBA,RUBELLA ( GERMAN MEASLES ) AVIDITY TEST
node.undefined8: Rubella or German measles is caused by Rubella virus, a type of RNA virus. Rubella infection is mild and characterised by fever, macular rash and lymphadenopathy. Infection is transient and usually resolves without any treatment. However rubella infection in pregnant female, especially in first trimester, can lead to serious congenital malformations in the baby. Antibody avidity measures the binding affinity of IgG antibody after infection. This affinity increases with time. With maturation of specific immune response, low avidity antibodies are replaced by high avidity usually after five months of infection. Rubella IgG antibody avidity test is used to distinguish between recent and remote infection. Avidity testing is most useful in early pregnancy to rule out acute rubella infection in first trimester, when risk of developing congenital malformations is highest. This test is done by Enzyme-linked Fluorescent assay (ELFA) method. Avidity may be low, intermediate or high. Specific low avidity IgG favours acute infection as affinity is not so strong enough. Presence of high avidity antibody results from remote infection as these antibodies have been around from quite some time leading to stronger bonds.

node.name: SERUM FOR CRYPTOCOCCAL ANTIGEN
node.undefined6: serum cryptococcal antigen, serum cryptococcal antigen test, CRYPT, ,SERUM FOR CRYPTOCOCCAL ANTIGEN
node.undefined8: Cryptococcosis is an invasive fungal infection caused by Cryptococcus neoformans or Cryptococcus gattii. Infection is usually acquired via the pulmonary route. Approximately half of the patients with symptomatic disease have a predisposing immunosuppressive condition such as AIDS, steroid therapy, lymphoma, or sarcoidosis. Symptoms may include fever, headache, dizziness, ataxia, somnolence and cough. While the majority of C. neoformans infections occur in immunocompromised patient populations, C. gattii is has a higher predilection for infection of healthy hosts. In addition to the lungs, cryptococcal infections frequently involve the central nervous system (CNS), particularly in patients infected with HIV. Untreated CNS cryptococcosis is invariably fatal. Disseminated disease may affect any organ system and usually occurs in immunosuppressed individuals. The presence of cryptococcal antigen in any body fluid serum is indicative of systemic cryptococcosis. Disseminated infection is usually accompanied by a positive serum test. Higher?Cryptococcus?antigen titers appear to correlate with more severe infections. Declining titers may indicate regression of infection. However, monitoring titers to cryptococcal antigen should not be used as a test of cure or to guide treatment decisions, as low level titers may persist for extended periods of time following appropriate therapy and the resolution of infection. A negative result does not preclude diagnosis of cryptococcosis, particularly if only a single specimen has been tested and the patient shows symptoms consistent with cryptococcosis. A positive result is indicative of systemic cryptococcosis, however all test results should be reviewed in light of other clinical findings.

node.undefined6: sperm dna fragmentation test, sperm dna fragmentation , spermd, SPERMO,SPERM DNA FRAGMENTATION
node.undefined8:
Sperm DNA Fragmentation Test 

The spermatozoa chromatin is a tightly packed structure because of disulfide cross linkages between protamines that allow compaction of nuclear head and protect the DNA from stress and breakage.

Cause of Sperm DNA Fragmentation:

The origin of Sperm DNA Fragmentation is multifactorial. Some of the factors associated with increased sperm DNA damage are tobacco use,chemo therapy, testicular carcinoma.

Human fertilization involves the direct interaction of the sperm and the oocyte, fusion of the cell membranes, and union of male and female gamete genomes. Although a small percentage of spermatozoa from fertile men also possess detectable levels of DNA damage, which is repaired by oocyte cytoplasm, there is evidence to show that the spermatozoa of infertile men possess substantially more DNA damage and that this damage may adversely affect reproductive outcomes.

Importance of Sperm DNA Fragmentation test in Infertile Couples:

Sperm DNA fragmentation defects can help couples decide on what fertility modality and possible lifestyle modifications they can employ that may increase their chances of conception. ICSI is advised when DFI is above cut off levels. There is higher rate of DNA damage in ejaculated or epididymal sperm than intratesticular spermatozoa, hence use of intratesticular from high DFI men is recommended for ICSI.There is evidence to suggest that sperm DNA damage is associated with poor pregnancy outcome after standard IVF

node.name: TORCH IGG
node.undefined6: torch igg, torg, torch igg igm, torch igg profile , TORG,TORCH IGG
node.undefined8: Mother can pass certain infections to the foetus in-utero or during delivery which can cause birth defects in the baby. Early detection of these infections is crucial to prevent congenital anomalies and complication. TORCH panel is a group of tests used to screen newborn (with signs/symptoms or maternal history) and pregnant women (with past bad obstetric history or first trimester infection) to detect IgG antibodies in serum against 4 infections viz. toxoplasma, rubella, cytomegalovirus and herpes. These antibodies are produced by immune system when exposed to the infectious agents. Testing is done by ELISA/CLIA methods. A normal test result means undetectable IgG in the blood and indicates absence of infection. Positive test result is the presence of IgG antibodies against the infections tested in the panel. Presence of IgG indicates recent or past infection. If IgG is positive (especially in pregnancy) repeat testing is done and antibody levels of paired sera are compared. Rising titres in subsequent testing indicate recent infection. Usually this testing is carried out with IgM for better interpretation of results.

node.undefined6: tsh, tsh test, tsh level, what is tsh, t3, t4, thyroid , tsh ultrasensitive, tsh test cost, TSH,TSH (ULTRASENSITIVE),SERUM,thyroid profile, thyroid comprehensive profile, body profile, comprehensive body profile , para thyroid profile, amh profile, cancer detection profile female, cancer detection profile male, obesity profile,
node.undefined8: TSH (thyroid stimulating hormone) is the initial most important single test ordered to assess thyroid function and monitor effectiveness of thyroid hormone replacement therapy. It is secreted by pituitary gland and follows the biological clock with peak secretion at midnight and early morning and lowest concentration in evening. TSH regulates the synthesis and release of thyroid gland hormones (T3, T4) by a feedback mechanism. Thyroid disorders are the commonest endocrine abnormalities seen in the clinical practice. TSH testing is done by CMIA method. Ultrasensitive method is a very sensitive and specific, helps in early diagnosis of primary thyroid disorders and detects extremely low/undetectable levels in blood. Normal TSH rules out thyroid disease in majority. TSH is low in primary hyperthyroidism and secondary/ tertiary hypothyroidism. High TSH values are seen in primary hypothyroidism and secondary hyperthyroidism. Changes in TSH levels are also seen in few non thyroidal illnesses and certain drugs. Estimation of T3 and T4 is usually recommended for final diagnosis of thyroid dysfunction. TSH is also used for neonatal screening of hypothyroidism.

Positive results are noted in Metabolic conditions (e.g., diabetes mellitus, renal glycosuria, glycogen storage disease) Dietary conditions (e.g., starvation, high-fat diets) Increased metabolic requirements (e.g., hyperthyroidism, fever, pregnancy and lactation). node.undefined6: 24 hours urine urea, urine nitrogen 24 hours urine, urine urea 24 hr, ure24, URE24,URINE UREA 24 HOURS.
node.undefined8: 24 hours Urine urea is a quantitative urine test done on urine sample collected over 24 hours. It?s a measure of protein breakdown in the body within 24 hours. Urea excreted also reflects kidney function in the body. This test is mainly used to determine necessary protein intake in severely ill patients. Increased values are seen in patients with either increased protein intake or increased protein breakdown. It can also be seen in hyperthyroidism. Decreased values are seen in patients with malnutrition or liver disease etc. Levels also vary with age (lower levels in children). Lower levels are also found in pregnancy. The sample is collected in the following way in a specialized container: Discard the first urine in the morning. Later, collect all the in a special container for next 24 hours. Next day collect the first morning urine sample in the container.

node.name: VITAMIN B 12 (CYANOCOBALAMINE)
node.undefined6: b12, b12 d3, d3, vitamin b12 , b12 blood test, b12 blood test cost, cynocobalamine, B12,VITAMIN B 12 (CYANOCOBALAMINE)
node.undefined8: Vitamin B12 is important for DNA synthesis, formation & maintenance of myelin sheaths, the synthesis of neurotransmitters, erythropoiesis and maintenanc of the methyl groups transfers required for numerous methylation reactions such as DNA-methylation. Clinical vitamin B12 deficiency includes two main manifestations: Hematological and/or Neuropsychiatric disorders The symptoms of early Vit B12 deficiency can often be missed as the symptoms of early deficiency are not very specific. Symptoms of Vit B12 deficiency can develop when the total Vitamin B12 is still within the laboratory reference range, therefore total Vitamin B12 level in the blood may not be indicative of true Vitamin B12 deficiency?It is a late marker of Vit B12 deficiency. Changes in the Total B12 result may not occur until the patient is already Vitamin B12deficient. Measuring total Vitamin B12 can underestimate Vitamin B12 deficiency because the portion of Holotranscobalamin (HoloTC) within the total Vitamin B12 is not linear over the whole serum Vitamin B12 concentration range. This means that total Vitamin B12 concentrations may be within the reference range but the concentration of HoloTC may be low. Hence it is advisable not to rely only on serum Vit B12 levels alone for diagnosing Vit B12 deficiency. As Total B12 test suffers from a number of important limitations.

node.name: WESTERN BLOT FOR HIV I & II
node.undefined6: wblot, western blot for HIV i & ii, WBLOT,WESTERN BLOT FOR HIV I & II
node.undefined8: Western blot is a technique that is very useful for protein detection as it allows to quantify the protein expression as well. It enables to identify the specific protein from mixture of proteins extracted from cells as well as evaluation of their size and amount. Western blotting can produce qualitative and semi-quantitative data about the protein of HIV. Western blotting (protein blotting or immunoblotting) is a rapid and sensitive assay for detection and characterization of proteins. It is based on the principle of immunochromatography where proteins are separated into polyacrylamide gel according to their molecular weight. The HIV-1 viral antigens are purified and then separated by SDS gel electrophoresis. SDS denatures viral components and yields proteins which migrate in the gel according to their molecular weight to produce various bands. Low molecular weight components migrate faster and are found at the bottom of the gel, while high molecular weight proteins remain near the top. They are then transferred from SDS-PAGE gel on to nitrocellulose membrane, which is also impregnated with HIV-2 antigen(gp36) and a control band. The membrane is cut and packaged as strips. Antibodies to HIV- 1 & 2 if present, bind to viral antigens located on the strip. Unbound material is washed off and then the strip is incubated with anti-human IgG conjugated to alkaline phosphatase (AP). After washing the unbound conjugate, substrate (BCIP/NBT) is added which results in the staining of bands. If antibodies to HIV-1 antigens are present in the sera, any two ENVELOPE with one or more of the following bands will be seen: p17, p24, p31, gp41, p51/p55, p66, gp120 & gpl60. If antibodies to HIV-2 antigens are present, HIV-2 band is also observed along with some of the other bands.

node.undefined8: EBV (VCA) - IgG is a test used to diagnose Epstein - Barr Virus infection, the most common cause of infectious mononucleosis. VCA is viral Capsid Antigen which can be detected in the infected individuals along with antigens like Early Antigen Epstein - Barr Nuclear Antigen. VCA - IgG appears in the acute phase of EBV infection, peaks at 2 to 4 weeks after onset , declines slightly then persists for the rest of a person's life . In general rising VCA - IgG levels tend to indicate an activate EBV infection while falling concentrations tend to indicate a recent EBV infection that is resolving.

node.name: LACTATE
node.undefined6: lactate, lac, LAC,LACTATE
node.undefined8: Lactate, the anion that results from dissociation of lactic acid, is a product of glucose metabolism.:sp ecifically it is the end product of anaerobic glycolysis. node.name: SERUM TRANSFERRIN
node.undefined6: serum transferrin, TRAN,SERUM TRANSFERRIN
node.undefined8: Transferrins are iron binding blood plasma glycoprotein that control the level of free iron. Transferrin glycoproteins bind iron tightly but reversibly. An increased plasma transferrin level is often seen in patients from iron deficiency anemia, during pregnancy, with increased use of oral contraceptives. A decreased plasma transferrin can be seen in iron overload diseases, protein malnutrition. An absence of transferrin results from a rare genetic disorder known as atransferrinemi a, a condition characterized by anemia, hemosiderosis in the heart and liver.

Thyroid Function test (TFT)

Thyroid function testing is usually done with TSH, T3,T4. The price of this test is Rs 500/- Only.

If you would like to read more about thyroid testing please click here 

Thyroid testing has now evolved and people prefer to do TSh along with FREE T3 and T4 rather than just Total T3 and Total T4. This is because the Free component is usually the active component and is usually the more effective one.

The first test to be done is usually the TSH. In hypothyroidism, the TSH will be high. In hyperthyroidism, it will be low. The FT3,FT4 is usually used to monitor acute changes in thyroid especially in HYPERthyroidism and Graveâ€™s disease.

node.undefined6: tibc, TIBC,TIBC
node.undefined8: Total iron binding capacity or transferrin iron binding capacity is a test used to measure the blood's capacity to bind iron with transferrin. TIBC is most frequently used along with a serum iron test to evaluate people suspected of having either iron deficiency anemia or iron overload. High levels of TIBC are found in iron deficiency anemia, pregnancy. Low levels of TIBC are associated with iron or lead poisoning, liver damage, frequent blood transfusions, hemolytic anemia, hemochromato sis.
